ai elitism of the Edo regime, and then to the nostalgic patriotism of the Meiji state. Kendo was later influenced in the 1930s and 1940s by ultranationalist militarists and ultimately by the postwar government, which sought a gentler form of nationalism to rekindle appreciation of traditional culture among Japan’s youth and to garner international prestige as an instrument of "soft power." Today kendo is becoming increasingly popular internationally. But even as new organizations and clubs form around the world, cultural exclusiveness continues to play a role in kendo’s ongoing evolution, as the sport remains closely linked to Japan’s sense of collective identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aKendo. 0aSwordplayzJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  abamboo.  abogu.  acollective identity.  acombat.  acultural studies.  aedo period.  afighting styles.  afights.  aglobal sport.  ahistory of kendo.  ahistory.  ainventing tradition.  ajapan.  ajapanese history.  ajapanese martial arts.  ajapanese studies.  ajapanese.  akendo.  akenjutsu.  amartial arts.  amedieval schools.  ameiji period.  amilitary training.  amuromachi period.  anationalism.  aphysical activity.  apractice of honor.  aprotective armor.  asamurai.  ashinai.  asoft power.  asports.  aswordsmanship.  atraditional culture.  awar.  awarriors.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028437140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095994140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959941/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  a